Tips to make the kids ready for fancy dress:

1. Choose the character of their choice. Mine is fascinating by Indian mythology and Gods. So we chose her character accordingly.

2. Keep talking to them about the character and the event to make them mentally prepared.

3. Try making most of the props at home rather than purchasing them. Not only the Hand made props make a good impact on the audience and judges but the child also gets involved in the entire process.

4. If possible do an outfit rehearsal at home.

5. Feed them well and keep them well rested before the event.

6. MOST IMPORTANT: Make them wear the heavy jewellery and props just 5 minutes prior to their number so that they don’t get irritated

7. Carry their favourite snacks to keep them full and handle any last moment tantrum

5. Let them know it’s okay to make mistakes. Let them erase and write again. Avoid scolding.
6. Schedule a regular study time/ routine.
7. Set up a HW friendly area. It should be airy and well lit.
8. Keep distractions to minimum. No TV, loud music or phone calls.
9. If they say no to HW even after trying all these points talk to them, don’t yell. Stay calm and try breaking the HW into sittings of 5-7 minutes each.
10. Lastly, limit the number of pages. 2 pages of HW is enough for a 5 year old child. Talk to the school if they are giving more than 2-3 pages of HW.

6 healthy pooris for your kid’s tiffin.

1. Plain/ Ajwain Poori

2. Dal Poori: Knead the atta with cooked dal (you can use leftover dal too), turmeric powder, salt and coriander leaf. Make pooris.

3. Palak (Spinach) Poori: Knead the atta with fresh Palak puree and salt. Make pooris.

4. Beetroot Poori: Knead the atta with fresh beetroot juice and salt. Make pooris.

5. Ragi Poori: Take 1/2 cup ragi flour, 1/2 cup wheat flour and salt. Add water little by little (less than 1/2 cup) and knead this to make the dough. Keep it covered for 15 mins. Then open and knead again once. Now you can make the pooris

6. Masala Poori: Take aata, ajwain, turmeric powder, salt, freshly chopped methi (fenugreek) leaves (or Kasuri methi). Knead with lukewarm water to make the dough. Make pooris.

We as a couple prefer travelling to places that are rich in history and culture. We prefer natural beauty over man made ones. We like visiting not only the cities but also the smaller towns and suburbs to know more about the locals, their lifestyle and if possible we never miss a chance to spend time as locals!!

So this year when we decided to travel, we knew it would be VIETNAM 🇻🇳. 

One of the world’s greatest history, such rich culture, unparalleled natural beauty, their amazing coffee and such warm people, you name it and Vietnam has it all!!

It’s just day 1 and I can’t wait to see what the next 6 days have in store for us! 

Stay tuned for more updates! 🙂🙂

Vietnam Day 1 & 2: Hanoi (The Capital city)

Day 1: We took some rest after checking in the hotel. And then in the evening we exported the city, visited the weekend night market, did some shopping and enjoyed the suburban vibe.

Day 2: Vietnam is known for it’s great history. We started the day by visiting the world famous Hoa Lo Prison.  Built by the French to hold Vietnamese prisoners, the prisoners were kept in such subhuman conditions. We thought we would cover the prison in 1-2 hours but it actually took us more than 3 hours.

Then we visited the temple of literature, Hoàn Kiếm Lake and the famous Note cafe. Had our dinner at a good Indian restaurant. Explored the area/ nightlife near our hotel and then called it a day.

Sharing some raw pics/ videos on the stories/ highlights.

Stay tuned for the update on rest of the trip 🙂

Vietnam Day 3: Ha long bay

On Day 3 we booked a day long cruise trip to Halong Bay. We booked the tickets from India itself through Klook.

Our Limousine van came to pick us up from the hotel at 8:30 am and took 2 hours to reach the harbour.

There we boarded our cruise which gave a tour of Ha long bay.

Hạ Long Bay is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and popular travel destination in Vietnam. The bay features thousands of limestone formations in various shapes and sizes. 

Ha Long Bay was officially recognised as one of the new 7 natural wonders of the world in 2011.

The beauty that you get to see there is absolutely surreal. The spectacular limestone pillars rising from the sea, the eroded notches, arches and caves creating a picturesque and beautiful landscape. It’s something that just can’t be captured by any means and I would definitely call it one of most beautiful experience of my life.

The cruise took us to 3 spots. The limestone caves, boating through the caves in the bamboo boats and Ti Top beach.

While returning we witnessed the most beautiful sunset of our lives with their famous jasmine tea and cakes.

They dropped us back at hotel around 9pm. We had our dinner and called it a day! 

Sharing some raw pics/ videos on the stories/ highlights.

Stay tuned for the update on rest of the trip 🙂

7N/8D itinerary details:

Save and share for future reference!

Since we travelled with our 5 year old, we planned our trip in a manner that would be interesting both for us as well as her.

Also, Vietnam is a country that can’t be covered in 8-10 days. You need at least 20 days to cover it.

So here’s the 3 city that we did this time:

📍 3 days: Hanoi-  Capital city of Vietnam. A nice blend of their culture and modern vibe. The prison there is a must visit.

📍 3 days: Phu Quoc- The most beautiful island of Vietnam. Just book a beach side villa and you can have few relaxing days with some stunning views. We planned to visit Phu Quoc for the biggest theme park of the country. Also there’s Vinpearl Safari (we can’t go there), which is a famous attraction for kids.

📍 2 days: Ho Chi Minh city- The biggest city of Vietnam. It’s like India’s Mumbai. There are plenty of tourist attractions (Chu Chi tunnel tops the list). It had a nice vibe and great night life.

Few cities that we couldn’t cover this time but would surely do that soon-
📍Da Nang: It’s a coastal city known for its sandy beaches and history as a French colonial port. Also, famous for Bà Nà hills.

📍 Hội An: An Ancient Town famous for Chinese temples, a Japanese-designed bridge, wooden shophouses, French colonial houses, and old canals. Also know as ‘City of Lanterns’

📍Sapa: Sapa is known for its lush green rice terraces, cascading waterfalls, and misty valleys.

📍 Nha Trang: It’s a coastal city known for its beaches, diving sites and offshore islands. 

If you have any query you can ask in the comment section.

Vietnam Day 5: VinWonders Amusement Park

We planned to visit Phu Quoc for 2 reasons. One for its pristine white sand beaches and second for this amusement park.

VinWonders is the biggest theme park of Vietnam and we had read quite interesting reviews about it. So we really wanted to take Miss K there. 

We didn’t tell her about it and this came as a really great surprise for her. Though she couldn’t go for all the rides as she didn’t meet their height criteria in some of the rides. But we had an amazing time there. She loved their water rides and did it again and again. 
We also had an amazing experience at their Sea World. There were amazing shows going on all the time at different section of the parks and she loved the Mermaid Show🧜‍♀️ the most.
Then we went to their water park and had quite a fun there too.

And then it was time to witness the most amazing show of the day. We had to wait around an hour for that show. It started at sharp 7pm. The light and water show at the princess castle. Initially I thought it would be some nice light show that Miss K would like to see but within minutes I realised it wasn’t just any other show. What we saw in those 20 minutes is the most mind blowing show I have ever seen! We all had goosebumps!

So that’s how we ended the fantastic day. 
Took the free city shuttle (Phu Quoc has amazing free shuttle service throughout the city all day) and went back to our resort, of course after my daily dose of coconut coffee 🧋

Sharing some raw pics/ videos on the stories/ highlights.

Miss K has always been a playful child. And that’s what I have always wished for her. I want her to live each moment and preserve each memory before her childhood becomes a story!

There are so many things about my daughter that make me a proud mother. But what makes my heart swell with pride is when I see her acts of kindness and forgiveness. I wish I could learn those traits from her!
